### 3.1 Prohibited AI practices (Art. 5 EU AI Act)

The following AI practices are **legally prohibited** and must not be used under
any circumstances — regardless of the business purpose:

1. **Manipulation through subliminal techniques** or deliberate exploitation of
   cognitive weaknesses with the aim of materially influencing the behaviour of
   persons — where this causes significant harm (Art. 5(1)(a)).
2. **Exploitation of vulnerable groups** due to age, disability
   or social/economic situation (Art. 5(1)(b)).
3. **Social scoring** by public authorities or on their behalf to evaluate the
   social trustworthiness of natural persons (Art. 5(1)(c)).
4. **Purely algorithmic predictive policing** (risk assessment of future
   criminal offences based solely on profiling) (Art. 5(1)(d)).
5. **Untargeted scraping** of facial images from the internet or from
   CCTV footage to build biometric databases (Art. 5(1)(e)).
6. **Emotion recognition in the workplace and in educational institutions** — except
   for medical or safety-related reasons (Art. 5(1)(f)).
7. **Biometric categorisation** to infer race, political
   opinion, trade union membership, religious/philosophical
   beliefs, sex life or sexual orientation (Art. 5(1)(g)).
8. **Real-time remote identification** using biometric methods in publicly
   accessible spaces for law enforcement purposes — except in narrowly defined
   exceptions with judicial authorisation (Art. 5(1)(h)).

_Violations can be sanctioned under Art. 99 EU AI Act with fines of up to **EUR 35 million** or
**7 % of worldwide annual turnover**._

### 3.2 Do / Don't for employees _(DSK OH KI 2024)_

**✅ Do:**

- **No PII in prompts** — pseudonymise or anonymise customer, employee and applicant
  data before passing it to an LLM (UUID-only pattern, Presidio pre-filter).
- **No client or customer data to cloud LLMs without a DPA** — third-country processing
  only via SCCs + TIA. Prefer EU-hosted alternatives (Mistral AI EU, Aleph Alpha).
- **Always review output** — validate LLM responses, never adopt them unchecked for
  decisions with legal effect (Art. 22 GDPR).
- **Demand sources** — for RAG/fact-relevant use cases, insist on grounding +
  source citation. Do not pass on hallucinations.
- **Four-eyes principle** for critical decisions, especially in the
  HR context, in credit decisions and in customer service.

**🔴 Don't:**

- **No applicant evaluation by AI alone** — violates Art. 22 GDPR
  and § 26 BDSG; HR use cases are high-risk (Annex III No. 4).
- **No sensitive data** (health, religion, sexual orientation) in
  AI workflows without an Art. 9 GDPR legal basis and a DPIA.
- **No model tuning with personal data** without a documented
  legal basis and the ability to delete trained models.
- **No unauthorised introduction of AI tools** without prior approval — all
  new AI services must go through a section 2 entry and a data protection review.

